</md></sn><sn><md>### Determining Latitude Geometric Concepts

![img](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Nh-em0n/QDoc/main/BCS/Geography/05.1.The%20Universe%20and%20Our%20Earth/resources/latitude-dgrm4.png)

:::.row
:::.col-12 .col-md-6

To understand how latitude is calculated geographically, it helps to look at the Earth as a sphere:

* The total angular measurement around the centre circle of the Earth is $360^\circ$.
* These angles are divided systematically into **degrees** ($^\circ$), **minutes** ($'$), and **seconds** ($''$).
:::

:::.col-12 .col-md-6
* If a line is drawn from any place on the Earth to its center, that line creates an angle with the **equatorial plane**. The value of that angle equals the latitude of that specific place.
* A location north of the equator is designated as **north latitude**.
* A location south of the equator is designated as **south latitude**.

:::
:::
</md></sn><sn><md>:::.row
:::.col-12 .col-md-6
#### Famous Lines of Latitude

Specific parallels are widely recognized due to their geographic significance:

![img](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Nh-em0n/QDoc/main/BCS/Geography/05.1.The%20Universe%20and%20Our%20Earth/resources/latitude-dgrm5.png)
:::

:::.col-12 .col-md-6
| Parallel Name | Degree Value | Hemisphere |
| --- | --- | --- |
| **Equator** | $0^\circ$ | Neutral (Great Circle) |
| **Tropic of Cancer** | $23.5^\circ\text{ N}$ | Northern Hemisphere |
| **Tropic of Capricorn** | $23.5^\circ\text{ S}$ | Southern Hemisphere |
| **Arctic Circle** | $66.5^\circ\text{ N}$ | Northern Hemisphere |
| **Antarctic Circle** | $66.5^\circ\text{ S}$ | Southern Hemisphere |
